1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,540
In this demo, we will see how to use

2

00:00:02,540  -->  00:00:08,860
the Hugging Face high level API to use some pre trained large language models.

3

00:00:08,860  -->  00:00:14,130
Specifically, we will go through a few examples of how to use these models.

4

00:00:14,130  -->  00:00:16,510
We'll see how to summarize text,

5

00:00:16,510  -->  00:00:18,390
how to generate new text,

6

00:00:18,390  -->  00:00:21,730
how to classify text samples, and so on.

7

00:00:21,730  -->  00:00:25,745
First of all, to use the high level API from Hugging Face,

8

00:00:25,745  -->  00:00:30,150
we need to import the pipeline function from the transformers.

9

00:00:30,150  -->  00:00:33,630
Having this function, let's see how we can summarize some text.

10

00:00:33,630  -->  00:00:35,710
To do this, first of all,

11

00:00:35,710  -->  00:00:41,250
we'll need to create a pipeline and specify the summarization task when we create it.

12

00:00:41,250  -->  00:00:46,705
This function will return a summarizer that we can then use to summarize our text.

13

00:00:46,705  -->  00:00:48,380
To use the summarizer,

14

00:00:48,380  -->  00:00:52,600
we need to provide the text to summarize and call the summarizer with

15

00:00:52,600  -->  00:00:58,035
some optional parameters such as max_length and min_length,

16

00:00:58,035  -->  00:01:03,560
which specifies the maximum and the minimum number of tokens in the result summary.

17

00:01:03,560  -->  00:01:08,860
A single call to a summarizer might return multiple different summaries.

18

00:01:08,860  -->  00:01:11,620
To get a text of a single summary,

19

00:01:11,620  -->  00:01:16,500
we need to get the value of the summary text from the first summary.

20

00:01:16,500  -->  00:01:19,735
Now let's see how we can generate some text.

21

00:01:19,735  -->  00:01:22,180
The process here is very similar.

22

00:01:22,180  -->  00:01:26,260
We create a pipeline and then we provide a prompt that will

23

00:01:26,260  -->  00:01:30,700
be used as a starting point for the model to generate follow up text.

24

00:01:30,700  -->  00:01:33,760
We can also provide additional parameters here,

25

00:01:33,760  -->  00:01:36,600
like max_length, as we did before,

26

00:01:36,600  -->  00:01:39,980
and the maximum number of sequences to return.

27

00:01:39,980  -->  00:01:45,600
As before, the output that we get from the generator is similar to what we got before.

28

00:01:45,600  -->  00:01:47,520
To get the generated text,

29

00:01:47,520  -->  00:01:52,040
we need to get the first sequence and use the generated text field from it.

30

00:01:52,040  -->  00:01:53,440
If you look at this text,

31

00:01:53,440  -->  00:01:55,060
it says that the scientists from

32

00:01:55,060  -->  00:01:59,260
this university created a new drug and so on and so forth.

33

00:01:59,260  -->  00:02:04,160
It looks like a reasonably generated text about a potential news article.

34

00:02:04,160  -->  00:02:07,200
The other thing that we will try to do is to classify

35

00:02:07,200  -->  00:02:11,260
text using so called zero-shot classification.

36

00:02:11,260  -->  00:02:15,840
A shot in this context means how many examples do we provide

37

00:02:15,840  -->  00:02:20,920
in a prompt to our model for it to understand what it should do.

38

00:02:20,920  -->  00:02:24,795
Zero means we don't provide any examples.

39

00:02:24,795  -->  00:02:27,160
If we have one shot classification,

40

00:02:27,160  -->  00:02:32,540
it means we provide a single example of how to classify text in a prompt itself,

41

00:02:32,540  -->  00:02:36,365
and we can use more than one shot classification as well.

42

00:02:36,365  -->  00:02:39,310
In this case, we again create a pipeline,

43

00:02:39,310  -->  00:02:42,010
specify the name of the task that we will do,

44

00:02:42,010  -->  00:02:47,190
and then we'll provide the text and the labels for a classifier to create the prompt.

45

00:02:47,190  -->  00:02:51,470
We also provide the hypothesis template that will become the part of

46

00:02:51,470  -->  00:02:55,845
the prompt and will help the model to figure out what are we asking it to do.

47

00:02:55,845  -->  00:03:01,090
Classifier returned a list of scores for each of the labels we have provided.

48

00:03:01,090  -->  00:03:02,640
If you look at the result,

49

00:03:02,640  -->  00:03:08,790
it specifies that this text about transformers is most likely about technology.

50

00:03:08,790  -->  00:03:13,000
Finally, Hugging Face is not limited to working just with text.

51

00:03:13,000  -->  00:03:15,420
We can also use it with images.

52

00:03:15,420  -->  00:03:18,180
For example, if we have an image like this that

53

00:03:18,180  -->  00:03:21,140
I got from one of the Hugging Face datasets,

54

00:03:21,140  -->  00:03:26,480
we can create a captioner model that will write a text caption for this image,

55

00:03:26,480  -->  00:03:30,255
so it will describe what is there on this image.

56

00:03:30,255  -->  00:03:32,820
To do this, I'll create a pipeline.

57

00:03:32,820  -->  00:03:35,390
Here I use a different way of creating

58

00:03:35,390  -->  00:03:39,370
a pipeline where it just provides the name of the model to use.

59

00:03:39,370  -->  00:03:42,030
If we scroll down and print the result,

60

00:03:42,030  -->  00:03:45,530
the text says two birds are sitting next to each other,

61

00:03:45,530  -->  00:03:48,310
which is pretty much spat on.
